	quest.0D17E828C723C2DF.quest_desc: [
		"This is your entrance to all electronic applications! You can't play with electricity before you even have any!"
		"before we build, a few key things need to be identified"
		""
		" -Alternating Current (AC) and Direct Current (DC) Are kind of one and the same in this mod. Just don't think about it."
		""
		"- Electrical equipment can fail! All electrical failures are heat based, the thermometer item can tell you the temperature of the object, but you should know you've messed up once the block starts smoking"
		""
		"-Polarity is important! Traditional Current is used with this mod, so imagine electricity runs from positive to negative terminal."
		""
		"- When connecting items into circuits, connect so that flow goes to the positive terminal from the block, and then out from the negative. "
		""
		"{@pagebreak}"
		"You need to like, actually understand electricity in order to mess with this mod, In essence, the only equation you'll need is Ohm's \"Law\" V=IR, In that:"
		"Voltage DROP = Current across resistive body * Resistance"
		"In other other words, The voltage drop across a resistive body will equal the current going through said resistive body multiplied by the resistance."
		"You'll use this often to make sure you don't blow things up."
		"I say \"resistive body\" because most, if not all components will have parasitic, unwanted resistance, capacitance, or other effects. The resistive body could be a dedicated resistor, or the parasitic resistance from long stretches of wire."
		""
		"&nI reccomend you watch the video: \"An intuitive approach for understanding electricity\" By Alpha Pheonix on Youtube.&r"
		""
		"{@pagebreak}"
		""
		"As for some other questions you might not get from the video:"
		"- Q:Why does resistance change in parrallel connections?"
		"A:Imagine electron flow, say a resistive body only allows 50% of the electrons pressing against through. Now imagine two of those resistors, you now have double the electrons passing through, doubling our current. This, represented as a single resistor in series, would be 1/2 the resistance of our initial thought experiment."
		""
		"-Q:What the helly is capacitance or inductance?"
		"A:Honestly, you do not have to worry about those two for this mod, but you can imagine them as opposites. Inductance is often generated by a retained electromagnetic field, pushing electrons. Capacitance is often generated by an electron storing body. Inductance will try very very hard to &ncontinue&r the flow of electrons after a change in electrostatic potential, while capacitance will try and &nstore&r the flow of electrons with a change in electrostatic potential. Resistance would not be the opposite, as it is not affected by the change in electron flow/potential. (In fact, conductance would be! Conductance is quite literally the inverse of resistance, set it to the power of -1 and you'll find conductance)"
		""
		"-Q: Rated versus maximum voltage, and wattage?"
		"A: Wattage is a unit of power over time, the unti of voltage is obviously volts, and current would be amperes, an ampere is just a columb over a second, so by multiplying the two factors together, we can get a unit of a volt*columb/s, or 1 W. It is a unit of power, and indicates nothing more than energy flow. In this case, when energy is lost in electron flow, it is often lost through heat. In this mod, it is completely lost through heat. Therefore, maximum wattage is the maximum energy in heat the object can dissipate per second. As for rated V/W, it is simply the reccomended V/W the object should recive."
		"Also, all of these ratings and maximums are relative, so it's not like you're garunteed to blow up as soon as you exceept 120V with a lightbulb."
	]
