	quest.1DB939C97C64EB37.quest_desc: [
		"Okay, This is a big step, I know, but it's a wildly important one."
		"In order for a generator to function, the electrical windings on it's exterior must conenct in a way such that the commutator connects to the coils in an alternating fashion. Powergrid makes this easy for us in two ways:"
		""
		"&oPlease Ponder for more details&r"
		""
		"-Generator housing and copper coils"
		"Connect copper coils like you would with a mechanical belt, right click on two shelves. No custom windings must be made, as placing generator housing between two differently axied coils will allow for them to be connected easily"
		""
		"-Device connectors"
		"These little guys will connect onto certain electrical parts and behave as the start and the end connection fro the hole block, or multiblock assembly. In this case, the device connector must tbe used to connect the coils to the commutator. Please note that the electrical source is the commutator and the coils combined, so connections must be made from the (+)Comm. to (-)Device Connector, then from (+)Device Connector, to (-)Comm. Please note that the device connector IS the coils, as it must be connected to the coils"
		""
		"How do we tune an output though? By taking a resitively changing item like a rheostat, we can introduce a resistance into the connection between our commutator and device connector, this allows us to change the output voltage at our end."
		"(The power resistor shown in the ponder is likely there to prevent a short circuit event in case the rheostat is turned to 0, I reccomend you allways start at an extremely high resistance and work your way down, to avoid blowing things up.)"
	]
	quest.1DB939C97C64EB37.quest_subtitle: "Build a simple shunt generator"
	quest.1DB939C97C64EB37.title: "Generation Station"
	quest.1DC6FBBFE29C62CA.quest_desc: [
